article.headline: Milwaukee rallies from 17-point deficit
article.linkText: Bucks win fourth straight, stay ahead of Heat
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Michael Redd scored 35 points, and the Milwaukee Bucks overcame the absence of Keith Van Horn and Washington's long-range shooting for a 116-107 victory over the Wizards on Wednesday night. The win was the fourth straight for Milwaukee, keeping the Bucks 1{ games ahead of fifth-place Miami in the Eastern Conference. The Bucks have the tiebreaker against the Heat, who beat Boston 104-101 Wednesday night. Desmond Mason scored a season-high 27 points, Toni Kukoc had 22 points and 12 rebounds and Brian Skinner had 15 points and 14 boards. The Bucks, coming off a win at New Jersey on Tuesday night, fell behind by 17 points in the second quarter and trailed most of the night until Mason's breakaway basket broke a 100-all tie with three minutes left. Mason was fouled on the play, and Kukoc swooped in to tap his miss through the hoop for a 104-100 lead. Brevin Knight, released by Washington last month, had five assists and scored 11 points, including a jumper at 1:05 that made it 106-100. As the buzzer sounded, he shook hands with Wizards coaches and players as green, purple and silver streamers cascaded onto the court. The Bucks had clinched a playoff spot while on the road, so this was their first chance to celebrate in front of their fans. Van Horn, who is averaging 16.5 points, sat out with a bruised right hand, which he injured against the Nets. The Wizards, who own the league's worst road record at 7-32, sank 12 3-pointers to Milwaukee's one and were shooting better than 50 percent from the arc before going cold in the fourth quarter and finishing 12-of-26. The Bucks were 1-for-10. Larry Hughes led seven Wizards in double figures with 19 points. Washington led 60-48 at the half.

Game notes
The Bucks declared injured rookie T.J. Ford out for the rest of the season and the playoffs because of a bruised spinal cord. Ford hasn't played since being hurt Feb. 24. ... Washington led by eight points after one quarter despite being outshot by Milwaukee. ... The Wizards had snapped a nine-game losing streak at the Bradley Center with 1 114-109 overtime win in December.
